  "text": "Analysis of graceful shutdown signal handling across three major production Go services reveals three distinct but complementary patterns for managing SIGTERM/SIGINT.\n\n**KUBERNETES/KUBERNETES** employs a context-based cancellation approach across multiple implementations:\n\nThe core library at `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go` provides `SetupSignalContext()` which returns a context.Context cancelled on either SIGINT (Ctrl+C) or SIGTERM (container shutdown). The implementation uses `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)` with a buffered channel of size 2 to allow registration of a second signal that triggers immediate `os.Exit(1)`, enabling forced termination if graceful shutdown stalls. The signal handler is protected by `onlyOneSignalHandler` which panics if called twice, ensuring single execution.\n\nThe companion file `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal_posix.go` defines `shutdownSignals` as `{os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM}` for non-Windows systems. Advanced interrupt handling appears in `pkg/util/interrupt/interrupt.go`, which implements a `Handler` type providing structured cleanup through `New()`, `Run()`, `Close()`, and `Signal()` methods. This handler manages `terminationSignals` (SIGHUP, SIGINT, SIGTERM, SIGQUIT) and uses `sync.Once` internally to ensure cleanup functions execute exactly once.\n\nThe reference implementation in `staging/src/k8s.io/sample-controller/pkg/signals/signal.go` and `signal_posix.go` demonstrates the standard pattern, while `staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/examples/leader-election/main.go` shows how context propagation enables automatic cleanup when contexts are cancelled.\n\n**PROMETHEUS/PROMETHEUS** uses explicit goroutine orchestration via the oklog/run library:\n\nAt `cmd/prometheus/main.go` (lines 1151-1176), a buffered channel `term` receives signals via `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)`. Rather than context propagation, Prometheus uses `run.Group` to manage all long-running components. Each service registers with `g.Add(execute func() error, interrupt func(error))`, providing both a function to run and an interrupt handler. When any component exits or a signal arrives, the run.Group calls all registered interrupt functions in reverse registration order, enabling precise cleanup ordering. The pattern includes dedicated DrainOnShutdown flags in notification configuration (line 582) and explicit timeout handling through `storage.remote.flush-deadline` to drain pending samples during shutdown. This approach explicitly orders cleanup: scrape manager stops before TSDB closes, rule manager stops before discovery managers, preventing false alerts and data loss.\n\n**GRAFANA/GRAFANA** combines explicit timeouts with coordinator patterns:\n\nAt `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/commands/cli.go`, the `listenToSystemSignals(ctx context.Context, s gserver)` function (lines 148-170) receives both shutdown signals via `signalChan` (SIGINT, SIGTERM) and reload signals via `sighupChan` (SIGHUP). The critical timeout implementation at line 162 uses `context.WithTimeout(ctx, 30*time.Second)`, enforcing a bounded shutdown window. The Server interface method `gserver.Shutdown(ctx context.Context, reason string) error` is implemented in `pkg/server/server.go` with a `shutdownOnce sync.Once` field ensuring single execution. The shutdown method delegates to `managerAdapter.Shutdown()` for background services and waits on context completion (lines 162-168), logging timeouts if they occur. HTTP graceful shutdown at `pkg/api/http_server.go` (lines 490-497) waits for context cancellation then calls `httpSrv.Shutdown()` with a fresh background context, using `http.ErrServerClosed` detection. The implementation also provides systemd integration through `notifySystemd(state string)` which sends socket notifications to systemd for proper service ordering.\n\nAll three patterns handle the core shutdown requirements: signal handler registration (buffered channels of size 1-2), shutdown timeouts (implicit via context in Kubernetes, per-component in Prometheus, explicit 30 seconds in Grafana), and cleanup ordering (context propagation in Kubernetes, reverse-order interrupt functions in Prometheus, layered shutdown in Grafana). The choice between patterns reflects architectural needs: Kubernetes favors simplicity through context propagation, Prometheus requires explicit component ordering, and Grafana emphasizes timeout guarantees for HTTP services. Each implementation drains connections before stopping goroutines by ensuring in-flight requests complete (HTTP.Shutdown) before background services terminate."
}

